'''Luis Fernando Díaz Marulanda''' (born 13 January 1997) is a Colombian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[left winger]] or [[left midfielder]] for {{German football updater|BaMunich}} club [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] and the [[Colombia national football team|Colombia national team]]. Regarded as one of the best wingers in the world, he is known for his pace, dribbling, and pressing ability.<ref>{{Cite web |date=20 March 2026|title=Ballon d'Or 2026 Power Rankings: Erling Haaland's hopes are slipping away while Harry Kane continues to put his foot down {{!}} Goal.com India|url=https://www.goal.com/en-in/lists/ballon-dor-2026-power-rankings/blte900f51820beae01|access-date=27 March 2026|website=www.goal.com|language=en-IN}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Swan|first=Rob|last2=Malyan|first2=Christy|last3=Murray|first3=Will|last4=Hepburn|first4=Daniel|date=10 November 2023|title=The 30 best footballers in the world right now - ranked in order|url=https://www.givemesport.com/best-football-players-in-the-world/|access-date=27 March 2026|website=GiveMeSport|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=27 March 2026 |title=Ranking the 10 best wingers in the world right now: Yamal, Olise, Kvaratskhelia… |url=https://onefootball.com/es/noticias/ranking-the-10-best-wingers-in-the-world-right-now-yamal-olise-kvaratskhelia-42551368 |access-date=27 March 2026 |website=OneFootball |language=es}}</ref>

Díaz began his professional career in the [[Categoría Primera B]] with [[Barranquilla F.C.|Barranquilla]], before moving to [[Atlético Junior]], winning the [[Categoría Primera A]], one [[Copa Colombia]], and one [[Superliga Colombiana]]. In 2019, he joined [[FC Porto|Porto]] for a reported fee of €7 million, winning two [[Primeira Liga]] titles, one [[Taça de Portugal]], and one [[Supertaça Cândido de Oliveira]]. After scoring 14 goals in 18 league games in the first half of 2021–22, [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] signed him in a transfer worth €45 million (£37.5 million). He won the [[EFL Cup]] and [[FA Cup]] in his first season, and was [[man of the match]] in the [[2022 FA Cup final|latter final]]. After winning the [[Premier League]] in [[2024–25 Premier League|2024–25]], Díaz joined German champions Bayern Munich for a fee of €75 million, including add-ons.

Díaz made his senior international debut for Colombia in 2018. He has earned over 60 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for the national team, helping Colombia to a third-place finish at the [[Copa América]] in [[2021 Copa América|2021]], where he was also awarded the [[Copa América awards#Golden Boot|Golden Boot]], and a runner-up finish in [[2024 Copa América|2024]].

== Club career ==
=== Atlético Junior ===
Luis Fernando Díaz Marulanda was born on 13 January 1997 in [[Barrancas, La Guajira]],<ref name="Soccerway"/> and began playing football at the age of six.<ref name=":2">{{cite news |last=Lang |first=Jack |date=28 May 2022 |title=Luis Diaz: The remarkable rise of 'Luchito', Liverpool's 'true miracle' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3332837/2022/05/26/luis-diaz-liverpool-champions-league/ |access-date=26 May 2022 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Nicknamed "Luchito", he attended a small football school run by his father.<ref name=":2" /> In 2014, at the age of 17, he attended an open trial hosted by [[Atlético Junior]] and impressed enough to join the youth team.<ref name=":2" /><ref name="Alexander2022" />

He was included in Colombia's 22-man squad for the 2015 Copa Americana de Pueblos Indígenas, due to his [[Wayuu people|Wayuu]] ethnicity.<ref name=":0">{{cite web |url=https://www.elespectador.com/deportes/futbol-colombiano/luis-diaz-el-wayuu-del-junior-de-barranquilla-articulo-714153 |title=Luis Díaz, el wayuu del Júnior de Barranquilla|trans-title=Luis Díaz, the Wayuu of Júnior de Barranquilla |publisher=El Espectador |language=es |date=20 September 2017|access-date=19 December 2018}}</ref> After impressing during the tournament, he joined the senior team of [[Atlético Junior]] in 2016, being immediately assigned to [[farm team]] [[Barranquilla F.C.|Barranquilla]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.habladeportes.co/quiero-consolidarme-junior-idolo-este-equipo-luis-diaz/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924141204/http://www.habladeportes.co/quiero-consolidarme-junior-idolo-este-equipo-luis-diaz/ |title="Quiero consolidarme en Junior y ser ídolo en este equipo": Luis Díaz |work=Habla Deportes |trans-title="I want to establish myself at Junior and become an idol in this team": Luis Díaz |language=es |date=21 September 2017 |archivedate=24 September 2017 |accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref> Given Díaz's slender build<ref name="Alexander2022">{{cite news |last1=Alexander |first1=Iñigo |title='Short and thin' – Luis Díaz's long road from Barrancas to Liverpool |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/may/26/short-and-thin-luis-diazs-long-road-from-barrancas-to-liverpool |newspaper=The Guardian |date=26 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220526145420/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/may/26/short-and-thin-luis-diazs-long-road-from-barrancas-to-liverpool |archive-date=26 May 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref> and a potentially [[malnourished]] appearance, he was given a dietary plan by Barranquilla to gain 10&nbsp;kg.<ref name="Alves2021">{{cite news |last1=Alves |first1=Marcus |title=Liverpool v Porto: Luis Diaz – Copa America star who 'seemed to have malnutrition problems' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59352834 |website=BBC Sport |date=24 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211124172939/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59352834 |archive-date=24 November 2021 |url-status=deviated}}</ref>

Díaz made his senior debut on 26 April 2016,<ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=James |date=18 August 2022 |title=Luis Diaz: Why Liverpool pounced, what he'll bring, his signature move and the 'Noodle' nickname |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3092002/2022/01/29/luis-diaz-why-liverpool-pounced-what-hell-bring-his-signature-move-and-the-noodle-nickname/ |access-date=8 April 2025 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> coming on as a second-half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a 2–1 [[Categoría Primera B]] home loss against [[Deportivo Pereira]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.winsports.co/futbol-colombiano/torneo-aguila/noticias/pereira-es-leyenda-vencio-barranquilla-y-sigue-lider-invicto-8941 |title=Pereira es leyenda: venció a Barranquilla y sigue líder invicto|trans-title=Pereira is legend: defeated Barranquilla and remain an unbeaten leader |publisher=Win Sports |language=es |date=26 April 2016 |accessdate=19 December 2018|archive-date=7 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707193147/https://www.winsports.co/futbol-colombiano/torneo-aguila/noticias/pereira-es-leyenda-vencio-barranquilla-y-sigue-lider-invicto-8941|url-status=dead}}</ref> His first senior goal came on 14 May, as he scored the winner in a 2–1 home defeat of [[Cúcuta Deportivo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.laopinion.com.co/cucuta-deportivo/cucuta-deportivo-no-pudo-ganar-en-barranquilla-111846 |title=Cúcuta Deportivo no pudo ganar en Barranquilla|trans-title=Cúcuta Deportivo could not win in Barranquilla |publisher=La Opinión |language=es |date=14 May 2016 |accessdate=19 December 2018|archive-date=3 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903114446/https://www.laopinion.com.co/cucuta-deportivo/cucuta-deportivo-no-pudo-ganar-en-barranquilla-111846|url-status=dead}}</ref>

On 6 June 2017, after already making his first team debut in [[2017 Copa Colombia|the year]]'s [[Copa Colombia]], Díaz was subsequently promoted to Junior's main squad.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://codigofutbol.co/sebastian-herrera-y-luis-diaz-pasaron-al-junior-penaloza/ |title="Sebastián Herrera y Luis Díaz pasaron al Junior": Peñaloza|trans-title="Sebastián Herrera and Luis Díaz moved to Junior": Peñaloza |publisher=Código Fútbol |language=es |date=6 June 2017 |accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref> He made his [[Categoría Primera A]] debut on 27 August, replacing [[Matías Mier]] in a 3–2 loss at [[Once Caldas]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elheraldo.co/rincon-juniorista/junior-cae-3-2-en-manizales-ante-once-caldas-396579 |title=Junior cae 3–2 en Manizales ante Once Caldas|trans-title=Junior fall by 3–2 in Manizales against Once Caldas |publisher=El Heraldo |language=es |date=27 August 2017 |accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref> and scored his first goal on 20 September in a 3–1 [[Copa Sudamericana]] home win against [[Cerro Porteño]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://colombia.as.com/colombia/2017/09/19/futbol/1505819690_902209.html |title=Junior 3–1 Cerro Porteño: Díaz, Teo y Chará le dan el pase a cuartos|trans-title=Junior 3–1 Cerro Porteño: Díaz, Teo and Chará give the qualification to the quarterfinals |publisher=Diario AS |language=es |date=19 September 2017|access-date=19 December 2018}}</ref>

Díaz became a regular starter during the [[2018 Categoría Primera A season|2018 season]], and scored his first goal in the top tier on 4 February of that year, by netting the game's only in a home success over [[Atlético Bucaramanga]]. He also added braces against [[Once Caldas]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/deportes/futbol-colombiano/junior-vencio-al-once-caldas-3-0-en-la-fecha-10-de-la-liga-197910 |title=Junior venció al Once Caldas 3–0 en la fecha 10 de la Liga|trans-title=Junior defeated Once Caldas by 3–0 in the round 10 of the League |publisher=El Tiempo |language=es |date=25 March 2018 |accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref> [[Atlético Huila]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://extra.com.co/noticias/deportes/f%C3%BAtbol/con-doblete-de-luis-diaz-junior-de-barranquilla-goleo-al-hui-447804 |title=Con doblete de Luis Díaz Junior de Barranquilla goleó al Huila en el Romelio Martínez|trans-title=With a brace from Luis Díaz Junior thrashed Huila at the Romelio Martínez |publisher=Extra Colombia |language=es |date=12 August 2018 |accessdate=19 December 2018|archive-date=4 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404172144/http://extra.com.co/noticias/deportes/f%C3%BAtbol/con-doblete-de-luis-diaz-junior-de-barranquilla-goleo-al-hui-447804|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Rionegro Águilas]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://colombia.as.com/colombia/2018/11/23/futbol/1542943100_703473.html |title=Junior derrota a Rionegro con goles de Jarlan y Luis Díaz|trans-title=Junior defeat Rionegro with goals from Jarlan and Luis Díaz |publisher=Diario AS |language=es |date=23 November 2018 |accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref> ending the campaign with 16 goals overall.{{citation needed|date=March 2024}}

=== Porto ===
==== 2019–2021: Development and adaptation to Portugal ====
On 10 July 2019, Díaz signed for [[Primeira Liga]] club [[FC Porto|Porto]] on a five-year contract,<ref>{{cite web |date=10 July 2019 |title=- Luis Díaz signed until 2024 |url=https://www.fcporto.pt/en/news/20190710-en-luis-diaz-signed-until-2024 |access-date=10 October 2019 |website=FC Porto}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Vazquez |first=Jonatan |date=11 March 2025 |title=Sponsorship agreement could draw Liverpool closer to contract with star |url=https://www.football-espana.net/2025/03/11/new-sponsorship-deal-liverpool-retaining-star-forward |access-date=8 April 2025 |website=Football España}}</ref> with the club buying 80% of his economic rights for a fee of €7&nbsp;million.<ref name=jogo>{{cite news |title=Agora sim: Luis Díaz assinou pelo FC Porto|trans-title=Now done: Luis Díaz signed for FC Porto |url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/agora-sim-luis-diaz-assinou-pelo-fc-porto-11070502.html |accessdate=10 October 2019 |work=O Jogo |date=2 July 2019 |language=pt}}</ref> [[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg|Zenit Saint Petersburg]] had also wanted to sign him, but he was convinced otherwise by compatriot former Porto players [[Radamel Falcao]] and [[James Rodríguez]], as well as his then-national team coach [[Carlos Queiroz]].<ref name=jogo/> Díaz also admitted that prior to his Porto move, he had signed a pre-contract with [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], but the move never materialised.<ref>{{cite web |last=Davies |first=Mathew |date=31 March 2019 |title=South American wonderkid claims he has Cardiff City agreement |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/south-american-wonderkid-luis-diaz-16054672 |access-date=21 April 2022 |website=Wales Online}}</ref>

He made his debut on 7 August in a 1–0 win at [[FC Krasnodar|Krasnodar]] in the [[UEFA Champions League]] first qualifying round first leg as a 55th-minute substitute for [[Romário Baró]],<ref>{{cite web |date=7 August 2019 |title=Luis Díaz debuta con el Porto en el triunfo de Champions League |trans-title=Luis Díaz debuts with Porto in the Champions League triumph |url=https://colombia.as.com/colombia/2019/08/07/futbol/1565205958_097015.html |access-date=10 October 2019 |website=Diario AS |language=es-co}}</ref> and six days later in the return game he scored his first goal, albeit in a 3–2 loss at the [[Estádio do Dragão]].<ref>{{cite web |date=13 August 2019 |title=Luis Díaz anota y Matheus Uribe debuta, pero Porto queda fuera |trans-title=Luis Díaz scores and Matheus Uribe debuts, but Porto go out |url=https://colombia.as.com/colombia/2019/08/13/futbol/1565730589_410794.html |access-date=10 August 2019 |website=Diario AS |language=es-co}}</ref> Domestically, he made his [[Primeira Liga]] debut on 10 August in a 2–1 loss at [[Gil Vicente F.C.|Gil Vicente]] as a substitute, and a week later scored for the first to wrap up a 4–0 home win against [[Vitória F.C.|Vitória de Guimarães]] as a starter.<ref>{{cite web |date=17 August 2019 |title=Luis Díaz anota en la goleada del Porto ante Vitoria Setúbal |trans-title=Luis Díaz scores in Porto's thrashing of Vitória Setúbal |url=https://colombia.as.com/colombia/2019/08/18/futbol/1566083499_625009.html |access-date=10 October 2019 |website=Diario AS |language=es-co}}</ref> In November, he, [[Mateus Uribe]], [[Agustín Marchesín]] and [[Renzo Saravia]] were suspended from the derby against [[Boavista F.C.|Boavista]] for having partied the night before.<ref>{{cite web |last=DN |first=Redacao |date=9 November 2019 |title=FC Porto afasta quatro jogadores por motivos disciplinares |trans-title=FC Porto sideline four players for disciplinary reasons |url=https://www.dn.pt/desportos/fc-porto-afasta-quatro-jogadores-por-motivos-disciplinares-11498374.html |access-date=11 October 2021 |website=Diário de Notícias |language=pt}}</ref>

In his first season in Portugal, Díaz totalled 50 appearances and 14 goals as Porto won the league and the [[Taça de Portugal]]. In [[2020 Taça de Portugal final|the final]] of the latter on 1 August 2020, he was sent off after 38 minutes in a 2–1 win over [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] at the [[Estádio Cidade de Coimbra]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Deus |first=António |date=2 August 2020 |title=Taça de Portugal: FC Porto conquista "dobradinha" – DW – 02/08/2020 |trans-title=Portuguese Cup: FC Porto wins "double" |url=https://www.dw.com/pt-002/ta%C3%A7a-de-portugal-fc-porto-conquista-dobradinha/a-54406385 |access-date=14 July 2021 |publisher=Deutsche Welle |language=pt}}</ref>

On 21 October 2020, he scored his first Champions League goal in a 3–1 defeat against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in the [[2020–21 UEFA Champions League|2020–21 season]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/match/2029279/ |title=Man. City 3–1 Porto |publisher=UEFA |date=21 October 2020}}</ref> On 23 December, Díaz came on as a 77th-minute substitute for [[Mehdi Taremi]] in the [[2020 Supertaça Cândido de Oliveira]] against ''[[O Clássico]]'' rivals Benfica, and scored to confirm a 2–0 win.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/noticias/fc-porto-bate-benfica-e-conquista-supertaca-pela-22-vez-13169898.html |title=FC Porto bate Benfica e conquista Supertaça pela 22ª vez|work=O Jogo |trans-title=FC Porto beats Benfica and conquers Super Cup for the 22nd time |language=pt |date=23 December 2020|access-date=23 December 2021}}</ref> The following 10 February, he was sent off in a 1–1 draw at [[S.C. Braga|Braga]] in a cup semi-final for unintentionally breaking [[David Carmo]]'s leg; compatriot Uribe was also dismissed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Luis Díaz saiu em lágrimas na reação à expulsão em Braga |trans-title=Luis Díaz left in tears in reaction to sending off in Braga |url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/fc-porto/detalhe/luis-diaz-saiu-em-lagrimas-na-reacao-a-expulsao-em-braga |access-date=15 February 2021 |work=Record |date=10 February 2021 |language=pt |archive-date=5 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220205032217/https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-bwin/fc-porto/detalhe/luis-diaz-saiu-em-lagrimas-na-reacao-a-expulsao-em-braga |url-status=dead }}</ref>

==== 2021–2022: Breakthrough and departure ====
On 11 September 2021, Díaz scored in a 1–1 away draw against [[FC Porto–Sporting CP rivalry|rivals]] [[Sporting CP]].<ref>{{cite web |date=11 September 2021 |title=Luis Díaz anota un golazo para el empate de Porto ante Sporting |trans-title=Luis Díaz scores a wondergoal for Porto's draw against Sporting |url=https://colombia.as.com/colombia/2021/09/12/futbol/1631397657_951619.html |access-date=27 January 2022 |website=Diario AS |language=es-co}}</ref> On 9 October, he scored the only goal of a 1–0 Champions League group stage win over [[AC Milan]].<ref>{{cite web |date=19 October 2021 |title=Luis Díaz le dio la victoria al Porto sobre AC Milán |trans-title=Luis Díaz gave Porto victory over AC Milan |url=https://www.vanguardia.com/deportes/futbol-internacional/2021/10/19/luis-diaz-le-dio-la-victoria-al-porto-sobre-ac-milan/ |access-date=27 January 2022 |website=Vanguardia |language=es}}</ref>

With two goals in a 4–0 win over [[Moreirense F.C.|Moreirense]] on 1 November, he reached five goals in his first six league games, best in the league;<ref>{{cite web |title=Luis Díaz vuela en Porto: doblete y goleador de la Liga de Portugal |trans-title=Luis Díaz is flying in Porto: brace and top scorer in Portuguese Liga |url=https://www.futbolred.com/colombianos-en-el-exterior/luis-diaz-marca-dos-goles-en-porto-vs-moreirense-es-goleador-de-primeira-liga-de-portugal-2021-2022-144693 |date=19 September 2021 |access-date=27 January 2022 |website=Fútbol Red |language=es}}</ref> On 28 November, he scored his tenth, a long-range effort in the 2–1 victory over [[Vitória Sport Clube|Vitória de Guimarães]]; this goal earned him the Primeira Liga Goal of the Month award.<ref>{{cite web |last=Romero |first=Pablo |date=28 November 2021 |title=Luis Díaz está imparable: vea su espectacular nuevo golazo en Portugal |trans-title=Luis Díaz is unstoppable: see his spectacular new wondergoal in Portugal |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/deportes/futbol-internacional/video-luis-diaz-hace-nuevo-gol-con-el-porto-en-portugal-635454 |access-date=27 January 2022 |website=El Tiempo |language=es}}</ref> His performances led to him being also named the league's Player of the Month and Forward of the Month for October and November.<ref>{{cite news |title=Luis Díaz é o Jogador do Mês da Liga Bwin |trans-title=Luis Díaz is the Player of the Month in the Liga Bwin |url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-bwin/fc-porto/detalhe/luis-diaz-e-o-jogador-do-mes-da-liga-bwin |access-date=27 January 2022 |work=Record |date=16 November 2021 |language=pt |archive-date=9 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220109002820/https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-bwin/fc-porto/detalhe/luis-diaz-e-o-jogador-do-mes-da-liga-bwin |url-status=dead }}</ref>

On 19 December, Díaz was named the league's Forward of the Month for the second consecutive month, after scoring four goals and providing three assists.<ref>{{cite news |title=Luis Díaz recebe distinção de melhor avançado do mês de dezembro da Liga |trans-title=Luis Díaz receives distinction of best forward of the month of December in Liga |url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-bwin/fc-porto/detalhe/luis-diaz-recebe-distincao-de-melhor-avancado-do-mes-de-dezembro-da-liga |access-date=15 February 2022 |work=Record |date=19 January 2022 |language=pt }}{{Dead link|date=November 2025 |bot=InternetArchiveBot }}</ref> Despite leaving Porto halfway through his final season, he was the joint seventh top scorer with 14 goals.<ref>{{cite web |date=15 May 2022 |title=Darwin Núñez é o melhor marcador da Liga, Taremi em segundo |trans-title=Darwin Núñez is the Liga top scorer, Taremi in second |url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/benfica/fc-porto/darwin-nunez-e-o-melhor-marcador-da-liga-taremi-em-segundo |access-date=23 May 2022 |website=Maisfutebol |language=pt}}</ref> Despite leaving Porto in January 2022, he was issued with a winner's medal after the club won the [[2021–22 Primeira Liga]] title.<ref name="liga22">{{cite web |last=Fernandes |first=Mariana |date=7 May 2022 |title=O recordista de minutos, o goleador, os três emigrantes. Os 26 campeões nacionais do FC Porto |trans-title=The minutes record holder, the goalscorer, the three emigrants. FC Porto's 26 national champions |url=https://observador.pt/especiais/o-recordista-de-minutos-o-goleador-os-tres-emigrantes-os-26-campeoes-nacionais-do-fc-porto/ |access-date=3 March 2024 |website=Observador |language=pt-PT}}</ref>

=== Liverpool ===
==== 2022–2023: Adaptation to England and Champions League final ====
[[File:Luis Díaz (portrait).jpg|thumb|150px|right|Diaz playing for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in 2022]]
On 30 January 2022, Díaz signed a five-year contract at [[Premier League]] club [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] for a reported €45&nbsp;million (£37.5&nbsp;million) with €15&nbsp;million (£12.5&nbsp;million) add-ons.<ref>{{cite web |date=30 January 2022 |author=Carroll, James |title=Liverpool complete Luis Diaz transfer from FC Porto |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/450841-liverpool-complete-luis-diaz-transfer-from-fc-porto#:~:text=Liverpool%20Football%20Club%20have%20completed,medical%20and%20finalising%20personal%20terms. |access-date=30 January 2022 |website=Liverpool FC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=30 January 2022 |title=Luis Diaz: Liverpool sign Colombia winger from Porto in five-year deal for initial £37.5m |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/60180371 |access-date=30 January 2022 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Hunter |first1=Andy |last2=Romano |first2=Fabrizio |date=30 January 2022 |title=Liverpool sign Luis Díaz for initial €40m and target Fulham's Fabio Carvalho |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/jan/30/liverpool-luis-diaz-tottenham-kulusevski-bentancur-transfer-news |access-date=8 April 2025 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Prior to signing for Liverpool, Díaz had attracted interest from [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]. Upon learning of Tottenham's bid, Liverpool changed their summer plans, and decided to sign Díaz on a permanent deal, after impressing Liverpool's then-manager [[Jürgen Klopp]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Carr |first=Declan |date=8 June 2022 |title=Liverpool set to steal Luis Diaz deal from under Tottenham's nose |url=https://www.vavel.com/en/football/2022/01/28/liverpool-fc/1099801-liverpool-set-to-steal-luis-diaz-deal-from-under-tottenhams-nose.html |access-date=30 January 2022 |website=Vavel}}</ref>

He made his debut on 6 February, coming on as a 58th-minute substitute for [[Curtis Jones (footballer, born 2001)|Curtis Jones]] in an [[FA Cup]] fourth-round game at home to [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]]. He assisted a goal by [[Takumi Minamino]] in a 3–1 win.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pritchard |first=Dafydd |date=6 February 2022 |title=Liverpool ease past Cardiff in FA Cup |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/60187991 |access-date=6 February 2022 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Thirteen days later, he scored his first goal for Liverpool in his second league start for the club in a 3–1 home win over [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] at [[Anfield]].<ref>{{cite web |date=19 February 2022 |title=Liverpool 3–1 Norwich: Reds come back to win at Anfield thanks to Mane, Salah and Diaz |url=https://www.football365.com/news/liverpool-3-1-norwich-reds-come-back-to-win-at-anfield-mane-salah-diaz |access-date=19 February 2022 |website=Football365}}</ref> In the [[2022 EFL Cup final]] on 27 February, he played the first 97 minutes of a goalless draw with [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] that his team won on penalties.<ref name="2022EFLCupFinal"/> On 3 May, he scored the second goal in Liverpool's 3–2 away victory over [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] in the Champions League semi-final, to secure his team's place in the final.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cunningham |first=Jack |date=4 May 2022 |title=Liverpool star Mane can equal incredible Lampard statistic against Villarreal |url=https://talksport.com/football/1100380/liverpool-sadio-mane-equals-frank-lampard-champions-league-record/ |access-date=8 May 2023 |website=talkSPORT |language=en-gb}}</ref> On 14 May, he started in the [[2022 FA Cup final]] against Chelsea, which Liverpool won 6–5 on penalties after a goalless draw, with Diaz being replaced by [[Roberto Firmino]] in the 98th minute, as he was named [[man of the match]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bennett |first=Charlie |date=14 May 2022 |title=Liverpool beat Chelsea to seal FA Cup after 6–5 penalty shootout win |url=https://www.thefa.com/news/2022/may/14/fa-cup-final-report---20220514 |access-date=16 July 2023 |publisher=The Football Association}}</ref> On 28 May, Díaz started in the 2022 Champions League final as Liverpool lost 1–0 to [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Real Madrid 1–0 Liverpool (May 28, 2022) Game Analysis |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=634861 |access-date=8 May 2023 |publisher=ESPN}}</ref>

On 30 July 2022, Díaz started for Liverpool in the club's 3–1 win over [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in the [[2022 FA Community Shield|FA Community Shield]] at the [[King Power Stadium]].<ref name="2022FACommunityShield">{{cite news |last=Hafez |first=Shamoon |date=30 July 2022 |title=Liverpool 3–1 Manchester City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62275194 |access-date=31 July 2022 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Train |first=Rob |date=30 July 2022 |title=Liverpool 3–1 Manchester City summary: score, goals, highlights, Community Shield 2022 |url=https://en.as.com/soccer/liverpool-manchester-city-live-online-scores-stats-and-updates-community-shield-2022-n/ |access-date=8 April 2025 |website=AS USA |language=en-us}}</ref> Diaz started the new months of the season by scoring four goals and providing three assists, including a brace in Liverpool's [[Liverpool F.C. 9–0 AFC Bournemouth|9–0]] win over [[AFC Bournemouth]], which equalled the [[List of highest-scoring Premier League matches#Biggest winning margin|joint-largest win in the history of the Premier League]].<ref name="BBC Match Report">{{cite web |last1=Hafez |first1=Shamoon |date=27 August 2022 |title=Liverpool 9–0 Bournemouth: Diaz, Elliott, Alexander-Arnold, Firmino, Van Dijk all score |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62614438 |access-date=28 August 2022 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref> However, on 9 October, Díaz came off for Roberto Firmino in the 42nd minute of a game against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] due to an knee injury.<ref>{{cite news |last=Media |first=P. A. |date=10 October 2022 |title=Liverpool's issues worsen as knee injury rules out Luis Díaz until December |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/oct/10/liverpools-issues-worsen-with-luis-diaz-out-until-december-with-knee-injury |access-date=4 November 2022 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> After seven months on the sidelines, Díaz made his return from injury on 17 April, replacing [[Cody Gakpo]] in the 81st minute of a 6–1 away win over [[Leeds United]].<ref>{{cite news |date=16 April 2023 |title=Leeds 1–6 Liverpool: Reds claim first win in five games to boost European hopes |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65228898 |access-date=3 May 2023 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> Having not registered a goal since 7 September 2022, Díaz returned to scoring ways on 30 April 2023, scoring Liverpool's second goal in their 4–3 home win over Tottenham Hotspur.<ref>{{cite news |date=28 April 2023 |title=Liverpool 4–3 Tottenham Hotspur: Reds edge Spurs in seven-goal thriller |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65363996 |access-date=3 May 2023 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

==== 2023–2025: Final year and Premier League champion ====
Díaz entered the [[2023–24 Liverpool F.C. season|2023–24 season]] with a new shirt number, changing from 23 to 7.<ref>{{cite web |last=Carroll |first=James |date=26 June 2023 |title=Luis Diaz to wear No.7 jersey for 2023–24 – Liverpool FC |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/luis-diaz-wear-no7-jersey-2023-24 |access-date=24 September 2023 |website=liverpoolfc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Lusby |first=Jack |date=26 June 2023 |title=Luis Diaz new Liverpool shirt number change confirmed |url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2023/06/luis-diaz-new-liverpool-shirt-number-change-confirmed/ |access-date=21 August 2023 |website=This Is Anfield |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 13 August, Díaz scored his first goal of the season as his side drew 1–1 against Chelsea in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite news |date=11 August 2023 |title=Chelsea 1–1 Liverpool: Axel Disasi scores on his debut to secure point for Chelsea |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66419907 |access-date=21 August 2023 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 19 August, he scored an acrobatic volley in a 3–1 win against Bournemouth.<ref>{{cite news |date=18 August 2023 |title=Liverpool 3–1 Bournemouth: Alexis Mac Allister sent off on Anfield debut |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66482704 |access-date=21 August 2023 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

On 30 September, Díaz scored against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in a Premier League away match, with the goal being disallowed by the [[Linesman (association football)|linesman]] for being [[Offside (association football)|offside]]. [[Video assistant referee|VAR]] did not intervene on the decision after an "unusually quick" review. After the match, [[Professional Game Match Officials Limited|PGMOL]] admitted that the offside ruling was a "significant human error" and Díaz should have been awarded a goal.<ref>{{cite web |title=PGMOL acknowledge error in Spurs v Liverpool match |date=30 September 2023 |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/3709629 |access-date=30 October 2023 |publisher=Premier League}}</ref> Liverpool lost the game 2–1.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fisher |first1=Ben |last2=MacInnes |first2=Paul |date=3 October 2023 |title=VAR audio from Luis Díaz's wrongly disallowed goal is released by PGMOL |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/oct/03/pgmol-prepared-to-send-liverpool-audio-relating-to-luis-diaz-gaffe-at-spurs |access-date=30 October 2023 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 5 November, in the first match he played since the kidnapping of his parents, Díaz came on as a substitute and scored a stoppage-time equaliser in a 1–1 Premier League draw away against [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Burt |first1=Jason |last2=Tyers |first2=Alan |date=5 November 2023 |title=Luis Diaz saves Liverpool blushes with emotional equaliser at Luton Town |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2023/11/05/luton-town-vs-liverpool-premier-league-live-score-updates/ |access-date=5 November 2023 |issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=3 November 2023 |title=Luton Town 1–1 Liverpool: Luis Diaz ends emotional week with late Liverpool equaliser |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/67253234 |access-date=5 November 2023 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 24 January 2024, he scored a goal for Liverpool in the [[2023–24 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] semi-final against [[Fulham F.C|Fulham]] which sent Liverpool to the [[2024 EFL Cup final|final]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Begley |first1=Emlyn |title=Fulham 1–1 Liverpool (2–3 agg): Luis Diaz goal sends Reds to Carabao Cup final |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68002571 |website=BBC Sport |date=23 January 2024 |access-date=24 January 2024}}</ref>

Díaz began the [[2024–25 Liverpool F.C. season|2024–25 season]] with three goals in three league matches, including a brace at [[Old Trafford]] in a 3–0 win against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] on 1 September 2024.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hytner |first=David |date=1 September 2024 |title=Luis Díaz strikes twice as dominant Liverpool win at Manchester United |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/article/2024/sep/01/manchester-united-liverpool-premier-league-match-report |access-date=2 September 2024 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> His goal against Brentford on 25 August 2024 was named [[BBC Goal of the Month]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |date=30 August 2024 |title=Vote for the MOTD2 Goal of the Month |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c74lvm7lezyo |access-date=7 October 2024 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 5 November, he scored his first [[List of UEFA Champions League hat-tricks|Champions League hat-trick]] in a 4–0 victory over [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/luis-diaz-hits-hat-trick-liverpool-beat-bayer-leverkusen-4-0-champions-league |title=Luis Diaz hits hat-trick as Liverpool beat Bayer Leverkusen 4–0 in Champions League |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |date=5 November 2024 }}</ref>

Liverpool won the [[2024–25 Premier League]], making Díaz the second Colombian to win the league after [[Juan Cuadrado]], who won it with [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in [[2014–15 Premier League|2015]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://rionoticias.co/luis-diaz-campeon-y-leyenda-colombiana-en-inglaterra/|title=Luis Díaz: campeón y leyenda colombiana en Inglaterra|date=28 April 2025|work=Rio Noticias}}</ref> Additionally, he scored 17 goals during the title-winning season, setting a personal best.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gallagher |first=Danny |url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2025/06/luis-diaz-had-his-best-season-yet-but-liverpool-should-consider-their-options/ |title=Luis Diaz just had his best season yet – but Liverpool face a painful decision |publisher=This Is Anfield |date=28 June 2025 }}</ref>

===Bayern Munich===
[[File:FC RB Salzburg gegen FC Bayern München (2026-01-06 Testspiel) 41.jpg|thumb|upright|Díaz playing for [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] in 2026]]
On 30 July 2025, Díaz signed for [[Bundesliga]] club [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] on a four-year deal for a reported fee of €75 million, including add-ons. He became the third Colombian player to represent the club, following [[Adolfo Valencia]] and [[James Rodríguez]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2025/07/fc-bayern-sign-luis-diaz-from-liverpool |title=FC Bayern sign Luis Díaz |publisher=FC Bayern Munich |date=30 July 2025|access-date=30 July 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=30 July 2025 |title=Bayern Munich sign Liverpool winger Diaz for £65m |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c1w8j9g5qleo |access-date=30 July 2025 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hunter |first=Andy |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/jul/30/luis-diaz-completes-655m-move-from-liverpool-to-bayern-munich |title=Luis Díaz completes £65.5m move from Liverpool to Bayern Munich |website=The Guardian |date=30 July 2025 |access-date=30 July 2025}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Colombia’s Luis Diaz Signs with Bayern Munich for $88M |url=https://colombiaone.com/2025/07/27/colombia-luis-diaz-signs-bayern-munich/ |access-date=30 July 2025 |website=Colombia One}}</ref> On 16 August, he made his debut and scored his first goal in a 2–1 victory against [[VfB Stuttgart]] in the [[2025 Franz Beckenbauer Supercup|DFL Supercup]]. By scoring his first goal for Bayern he did his former Liverpool teammate [[Diogo Jota]]'s gaming celebration as a tribute to him.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c9wyyw5wn9nt |title=Stuttgart 1–2 Bayern Munich |publisher=BBC Sport |date=16 August 2025 |access-date=16 August 2025}}</ref> A week later, on 22 August, he scored a goal and provided two assists on his Bundesliga debut in a 6–0 victory over [[RB Leipzig]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/matches/profis/bundesliga/2025-2026/fc-bayern-muenchen-rb-leipzig-22-08-2025/report |title=Harry Kane hat-trick as Bayern hit RB Leipzig for six in Bundesliga opener |publisher=FC Bayern Munich |date=22 August 2025 }}</ref>

On 4 November 2025 in a [[2025–26 UEFA Champions League league phase|UEFA Champions League league phase]] match against [[Paris Saint-Germain FC|Paris Saint-Germain]], Díaz scored twice in the first-half. Before half-time, he committed a foul that injured [[Achraf Hakimi]], and was sent off with a straight red card. Two weeks later, UEFA suspended Díaz for three games for "serious rough play".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cwywj30gjldo |title=Diaz gets three-game ban for Hakimi challenge |publisher=BBC Sport |date= 21 November 2025 |access-date= 14 December 2025 | first = Alex | last = Brotherton}}</ref> In January 2026, German TV viewers named Luis Diaz' goal against [[1. FC Union Berlin|Union Berlin]] on 8 November 2025 as German goal of the year 2025.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.sportschau.de/tor-des-monats/archiv/chronik20er/luis-diaz-wahnsinnstor-ist-tor-des-jahres-2025,tor-des-jahres-2025-sp-100.html&#x20;goal&#x20;of&#x20;the&#x20;year&#x20;2025 | title = Diaz' "Wahnsinnstor" ist Tor des Jahres | website = Sportschau.de | language = de | date = 31 January 2026 | access-date = 16 February 2026 | first = Markus | last = Wessel}}</ref> On 8 February 2026, he netted his first hat-trick for the club in a 5–1 victory over [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|TSG Hoffenheim]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20260208-diaz-treble-helps-bayern-crush-hoffenheim-and-go-six-clear |title=Diaz treble helps Bayern crush Hoffenheim and go six clear |publisher=France 24 |date=8 February 2026 }}</ref> A month later, on 18 March, he scored in a 4–1 win over [[Atalanta BC|Atalanta]] in the [[2025–26 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|Champions League round of 16]], reaching 14 goals and becoming the top Colombian scorer in the competition, surpassing the tally of [[Jackson Martínez]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://colombia.as.com/futbol/colombianos-por-el-mundo/luis-diaz-el-colombiano-con-mas-goles-en-la-historia-de-la-champions-f202603-n/ |title=Luis Díaz, el colombiano con más goles en la historia de la Champions |publisher=As.com |language=es |date=19 March 2026 }}</ref>

On 7 April, he scored the first goal in a 2–1 away win over Real Madrid at the [[Bernabéu (stadium)|Bernabéu]], securing his club's first victory at the stadium since 1 May 2001 and their first win over Real Madrid since 17 April 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/02a4-2055ba2b6033-0e7e190d47fb-1000--real-madrid-1-2-bayern-munchen-diaz-and-kane-pounce-for-sh/ |title=Real Madrid 1-2 Bayern München highlights: Luis Díaz and Harry Kane pounce in Champions League quarter-final first leg |publisher=UEFA |date=7 April 2026 }}</ref> A week later, on 15 April, he scored a crucial goal in a 4–3 win over Real Madrid in the second-leg, sealing his club's place in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20260415-kane-lauds-diaz-moment-of-magic-after-bayern-knock-out-real |title=Kane lauds Diaz 'moment of magic' after Bayern knock out Real |publisher=France 24 |date=15 April 2026 }}</ref> On 19 April, he provided two assists in a 4–2 victory over VfB Stuttgart, helping Bayern Munich secure their 35th Bundesliga title.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/matches/profis/bundesliga/2025-2026/fc-bayern-muenchen-vfb-stuttgart-18-04-2026/report |title=Bayern beat Stuttgart to win Bundesliga title! |publisher=FC Bayern Munich |date=19 April 2026 }}</ref> Furthermore, he became the first Bayern player to register at least 13 goals and 13 assists in a single Bundesliga season since records began in 2004–05.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tribuna.com/en/news/2026-04-19-matteo-politano-on-antonio-contes-napoli-future-we-dont-really-like-that-our-coach-is-alr/ |title=Luis Diaz becomes first Bayern player since 2004/05 to reach 13+ goals and 13+ assists in a Bundesliga season |publisher=Tribuna.com |date=19 April 2026 }}</ref>

== International career ==
[[File:Luis Díaz (112) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Díaz playing for [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]] in 2022]]

After representing [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]] at [[Colombia national under-20 football team|under-20 level]] in the [[2017 South American U-20 Championship]], Díaz was called up to the full squad on 27 August 2018, for [[Friendly (association football)|friendlies]] against [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]] and [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://diariolalibertad.com/sitio/2018/08/27/luis-diaz-convocado-a-la-seleccion-colombia/ |title=Luis Diaz, convocado a la selección Colombia|work=Diario La Libertad |trans-title=Luis Díaz, called up to Colombia national team |language=es |date=27 August 2018|access-date=19 December 2018}}</ref>

He made his full international debut on 11 September, replacing [[Juan Cuadrado]] in a 0–0 draw against the latter at the [[MetLife Stadium]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nuestrosdeportes.com/f%C3%BAtbol/selecci%C3%B3n/1940-con-el-debut-de-benedetti-y-luis-d%C3%ADaz,-colombia-empat%C3%B3-con-argentina.html |title=Con el debut de Benedetti y Luis Díaz, Colombia empató con Argentina|trans-title=With the debut of Benedetti and Luis Díaz, Colombia drew with Argentina |publisher=Nuestros Deportes |language=es |date=12 September 2018|access-date=19 December 2018}}</ref> Díaz scored his first international goal on 26 March 2019, equalising in a 2–1 friendly loss away to [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jee-ho |first=Yoo |date=26 March 2019 |title=S. Korea beat Colombia behind Son Heung-min's long-awaited goal {{!}} Yonhap News Agency |url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20190326010900315 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230626021622/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20190326010900315 |archive-date=26 June 2023 |access-date=10 June 2020 |work=Yonhap News Agency}}</ref> He was part of [[Carlos Queiroz]]' 23-man squad for the [[2019 Copa América]] in Brazil.<ref>{{cite web |date=31 May 2019 |title=James and Falcao head Colombia's Copa America squad |url=https://apnews.com/james-and-falcao-head-colombias-copa-america-squad-ef0a0a9ef05f468f9d2ff437c5d11b67 |access-date=10 October 2019 |website=Associated Press}}</ref>

Díaz was included in Colombia's squad for the [[2021 Copa América]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.as.com/en/2021/06/14/football/1623690475_049892.html |title=Colombia squad for 2021 Copa América: selected players absences... |publisher=AS.com |date=14 June 2021 |access-date=24 June 2021 |archive-date=28 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210628155615/https://en.as.com/en/2021/06/14/football/1623690475_049892.html |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=11 June 2024 |title=Liverpool star Luis Diaz can carry Colombia to Copa America glory in 2024 |url=https://www.goal.com/en/lists/liverpool-star-luis-diaz-can-carry-colombia-to-copa-america-glory-in-2024/blt8475f45c1ba369b4 |access-date=8 April 2025 |website=Goal (website)}}</ref> On 23 June, he scored the opening goal in a 2–1 first round loss to hosts [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] with a bicycle kick,<ref>{{cite news |date=24 June 2021 |title=Brazil 2–1 Colombia: Casemiro gives hosts controversial win deep in stoppage time |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/57592206 |access-date=24 June 2021 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> and on 6 July he scored their goal in a semi-final draw against Argentina, which ended in an Argentine victory following a penalty shoot-out.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://footballexpress.co.uk/copa-america-2021-argentina-1-1-colombia-post-match-analysis/ |title=Copa America 2021: Argentina 1–1 Colombia Post-match analysis |website=Football Express |date=24 June 2021 |access-date=7 July 2021 |archive-date=24 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230124140219/https://footballexpress.co.uk/copa-america-2021-argentina-1-1-colombia-post-match-analysis/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> Three days later, he scored twice, including the match-winning goal, in a 3–2 victory over [[Peru national football team|Peru]] in the third-place match.<ref>{{cite news |title=Copa America LIVE: Watch Colombia v Peru in third-place play-off plus score updates |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/live/football/57107455 |date=8 July 2021 |access-date=10 July 2021 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> He ended as joint-top goalscorer of the tournament alongside [[Lionel Messi]].<ref>{{cite web |agency=Associated Press |date=11 July 2021 |title=Colombia's Luis Diaz becomes Copa America joint top scorer with Lionel Messi |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/sport/football/2021/jul/11/colombias-luis-diaz-becomes-copa-america-joint-top-scorer-with-lionel-messi-2328619.html |access-date=23 December 2021 |website=The New Indian Express}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/luis-diaz-recebeu-trofeu-da-copa-america-e-elogiou-messi-e-um-orgulho-13966887.html |title=Luis Díaz recebeu troféu da Copa América e elogiou Messi: "É um orgulho"|trans-title=Luis Díaz received the Copa América trophy and praised Messi: "It's a pride" |work=O Jogo |language=pt |date=23 July 2021|access-date=23 December 2021}}</ref>

On 16 November 2023, Díaz scored both of Colombia's goals as they defeated Brazil 2–1 in what was the first time they had ever defeated the latter in a [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|FIFA World Cup qualifier]].<ref>{{cite web |date=17 November 2023 |title=Emotional Luis Díaz scores brace for Colombia with father in attendance |url=https://www.espn.com.au/football/story/_/id/38917501/emotional-luis-diaz-scores-brace-colombia-father-attendance-days-kidnaping-release |access-date=17 November 2023 |publisher=ESPN}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=17 November 2023 |title=World Cup qualifiers: Luis Díaz scores twice as Colombia stun Brazil, Uruguay beat Argentina |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/nov/17/football-world-cup-qualifiers-results-colombia-vs-brazil-uruguay-vs-argentina-luis-diaz |access-date=8 April 2025 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

On 21 June 2024, he was selected in the 26-man squad for the [[2024 Copa América]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Pérez |first=Miguel Ángel Prieto |date=21 June 2024 |title=Plantel de la selección de Colombia para la Copa América 2024: seleccionados, ausencias... |url=https://colombia.as.com/futbol/copa-america/plantel-de-la-seleccion-de-colombia-para-la-copa-america-2024-seleccionados-ausencias-n/ |access-date=15 July 2024 |website=Diario AS |language=es-co}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Garrick |first=Omar |date=22 June 2024 |title=Copa America 2024 squads: All 26-man selections from the 16 competing nations |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5558036/2024/06/17/copa-america-2024-squads-rosters-players/ |access-date=8 April 2025 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He would help his national team reach the [[2024 Copa América final|final]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://copaamerica.com/en/news/colombia-uruguay-match-recap-copa-america-2024 |title=Colombia Outlast Uruguay, Punch Ticket To The CONMEBOL Copa América Final |publisher=CONMEBOL |date=11 July 2024 |access-date=11 July 2024 }}</ref> where they lost 1–0 to Argentina after extra time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Chris |date=15 July 2024 |title=Martínez inspires Argentina to historic Copa América title in chaotic final |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/article/2024/jul/15/martinez-inspires-argentina-to-historic-copa-america-title-in-chaotic-final |access-date=15 July 2024 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Díaz is of [[Wayuu people|Wayuu]] origin.<ref>{{cite news |title=Luis Diaz: the indigenous star from Colombia's poorest community |url=https://www.besoccer.com/new/luis-diaz-the-indigenous-star-from-colombia-s-poorest-community-1143316 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240926023639/https://www.besoccer.com/new/luis-diaz-the-indigenous-star-from-colombia-s-poorest-community-1143316 |archive-date=26 September 2024 |access-date=13 January 2023}}</ref> His brother, [[Jesús Díaz (footballer, born 2004)|Jesús]], is also a professional footballer.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://co.marca.com/claro/futbol-internacional/liga-portuguesa/2022/07/15/62d1a6df22601d90588b4601.html |title=Jesús Díaz se desliga de Luis Díaz en su llegada a Porto: "Quiero escribir mi propia historia"|trans-title=Jesús Díaz breaks away from Luis Díaz on his arrival in Porto: "I want to write my own story" |date=15 July 2022|access-date=16 August 2022 |newspaper=Marca|location=Spain |language=es |archive-date=24 January 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230124132502/https://co.marca.com/claro/futbol-internacional/liga-portuguesa/2022/07/15/62d1a6df22601d90588b4601.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> In July 2023, Díaz got engaged to his girlfriend, Gera Ponce and they got married in June 2025.<ref>{{cite web |last=Durkan |first=Joanna |date=10 July 2023 |title=Salah's dance moves, Robbo reunites with Ox & an engagement – LFC holidays |url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2023/07/salahs-dance-moves-robbo-reunites-with-ox-an-engagement-lfc-player-holidays/ |access-date=10 July 2023 |website=This Is Anfield |language=en-GB}}</ref>

On 29 October 2023, Díaz's mother Cilenis Marulanda and father Luis Manuel "Mane" Díaz were [[Kidnapping|kidnapped]] by armed men on motorcycles at a gas station in their hometown of [[Barrancas, La Guajira|Barrancas]].<ref>{{cite news |date=29 October 2023 |title=Father of Liverpool's Luis Díaz missing in Colombia amid kidnapping reports |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/oct/29/father-of-liverpools-luis-diaz-missing-in-colombia-amid-kidnapping-reports |access-date=29 October 2023 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> His mother was rescued by police a day later, with a "major military search" announced to locate his father. Colombian President [[Gustavo Petro]] stated that "all the public forces have been deployed" and the following day, [[Military Forces of Colombia|General]] William Rene Salamanca announced a reward of up to 200 million pesos for information on Díaz's father's whereabouts.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hunter |first=Andy |date=29 October 2023 |title=Luis Díaz ordeal made it 'most difficult game' for Jürgen Klopp and Liverpool |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/oct/29/luis-diaz-ordeal-made-it-most-difficult-game-for-jurgen-klopp-and-liverpool |access-date=29 October 2023 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Díaz was absent for Liverpool's following Premier League match against [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]], with his teammate [[Diogo Jota]] holding up Díaz's shirt during a goal celebration.<ref>{{cite news |date=29 October 2023 |title=Luis Diaz: Major military and police search under way for Liverpool player's father |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/67257588 |access-date=30 October 2023 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> His father was released by the kidnappers on 9 November.<ref>{{cite news |date=9 November 2023 |title=Footballer Luis Díaz's father freed by Colombian guerrillas |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-67372903 |access-date=9 November 2023 |language=en-GB}}</ref>

In June 2024, leading up to the [[2024 Copa América]], Díaz appeared on Colombian singer, [[Ryan Castro]]'s song "EL RITMO QUE NOS UNE". He also appeared in the music video alongside Colombian national team teammates, [[James Rodriguez]] and [[Juan Fernando Quintero]] who also sang in the song.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://onefootball.com/en/news/video-luis-diaz-shows-off-new-talent-as-he-raps-in-colombia-song-39606299|title= (Video) Luis Diaz shows off new talent as he raps in Colombia song|date=10 June 2024|publisher=OneFootball}}</ref>

